## Output

Final assistant message MUST be JSONL only — one JSON object per line,
no prose, no fences. Harness parses lines where `.id` starts with
`REC-` or `RECON-` (the harness rewrites `.id` to a deterministic
`RECON-<sha256-prefix>` after parsing, so any short stub is fine).
Intermediate JSONL is fine; parser unions all assistant text.
Zero JSONL = run discarded.
Do not write `findings.jsonl` or any other output file in the workspace;
emit candidate JSONL in assistant text only.

All emissions are labeled `NEEDS-VERIFICATION` — the validator
decides what gets promoted. Do **not** demote to `AUDIT-CLEAN` just
because you cannot fully prove exploitability in budget; that is the
validator's call, not yours. The one exception is the categorical
non-issues above — skip those. If you spot anything else off, emit it.

## Schema (per line)

  {
    "id": "REC-<short-stub>",
    "slice": "{{ slice_name }}",
    "title": "one-line title of the bug or suspicion",
    "file": "<path>",
    "line": <integer or 0>,
    "function": "<fully-qualified demangled symbol (ns::Class::method) from stack frame #0 if a crash exists, else the defining function; no args/line/path; empty if none>",
    "class": "memory-safety|auth|injection|info-disclosure|crypto|race|boundary|deserialization|config|logic|side-channel|dos|other",
    "notes": "1-3 sentences: dangerous operation or broken check; missing/defeatable guard; configured untrusted path, or the exact reachability edge still unverified.",
    "confidence": "NEEDS-VERIFICATION"
  }

Audited the scope and saw nothing? One line:

  {"id":"REC-empty","slice":"{{ slice_name }}","confidence":"AUDIT-CLEAN","notes":"<1 sentence: what you reviewed and why nothing stood out>"}

## Budget

Wall-time: {{ timeout_secs }}s. When time runs short, emit JSONL for
